# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: amylase
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:amylase/acid-alpha-glucosidase] This gene encodes **lysosomal alpha-glucosidase**, which is essential for the degradation of glycogen to glucose in lysosomes.
[src:amylase/acid-alpha-glucosidase] Different forms of acid alpha-glucosidase are obtained by proteolytic processing.
[src:amylase/acid-alpha-glucosidase] Defects in this gene are the cause of glycogen storage disease II, also known as Pompe disease, which is an autosomal recessive disorder with a broad clinical spectrum.
[src:amylase/acid-alpha-glucosidase] Three transcript variants encoding the same protein have been found for this gene.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] ACTH is a hormone produced in the anterior pituitary gland that stimulates the adrenal glands to release cortisol, dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA), dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate (DHEA-S), and aldosterone.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] During the test, a small amount of synthetic ACTH is injected, and the amount of cortisol (and sometimes aldosterone) that the adrenals produce in response is measured.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] This test may cause mild side effects in some individuals.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] This test is used to diagnose or exclude primary and secondary adrenal insufficiency, Addison's disease, and related conditions.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] In addition to quantifying adrenal insufficiency, the test can distinguish whether the cause is adrenal (low cortisol and aldosterone production) or pituitary (low ACTH production).
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Adrenal insufficiency is a potentially life-threatening condition.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Treatment should be initiated as soon as the diagnosis is confirmed, or sooner if the patient presents in apparent adrenal crisis.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] This test can be given as a *low-dose short test*, a *conventional-dose short test*, or as a *prolonged-stimulation test*.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] In the low-dose short test, 1 μg of an ACTH drug is injected into the patient.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] In the conventional-dose short test, 250 μg of drug are injected.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Both of these short tests last for about an hour and provide the same information.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Studies have shown the cortisol response of the adrenals is the same for the low-dose and conventional-dose tests.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] The prolonged-stimulation test, which is also called a *long conventional-dose test*, can last up to 48 hours.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] This form of the test can differentiate between primary, secondary, and tertiary adrenal insufficiency.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] This form of the test is rarely performed because earlier testing of cortisol and ACTH levels in association with the short test may provide all the necessary information.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] The test should not be given if on glucocorticoids or adrenal extract supplement, as these will affect test results.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Stress and recently administered radioisotope scans can artificially increase levels and may invalidate test results.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Spironolactone, contraceptives, licorice, estrogen, androgen (including DHEA) and progesterone therapy may also affect both aldosterone and cortisol stimulation test results.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] To stimulate aldosterone, consumption of salt should be reduced to a minimum, and foods high in sodium avoided for 24 hours prior to testing.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Women should ideally undergo testing during the first week of their menstrual cycle as aldosterone (and occasionally cortisol) may be falsely elevated in the luteal cycle secondary to progesterone inhibition, leading to a compensatory rise in aldosterone levels.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Traditionally, cortisol and ACTH levels (separate lavender top tube) are drawn at baseline (time = 0).
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Next, synthetic ACTH or another corticotropic agent is injected IM or IV, depending on the agent.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Approximately 20 mL of heparinized venous blood is collected at 30 and 60 minutes after the synthetic ACTH injection to measure cortisol levels.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] ACTH samples are kept on ice and sent immediately to the laboratory, whereas cortisol does not need to be kept on ice.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Commonly reported reactions are nausea, anxious sweating, dizziness, itchy skin, redness and or swelling of injection site, palpitations (a fast or fluttering heart beat), and facial flushing (may also include arms and torso), but should disappear within a few hours.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Rarely seen, but serious side effects include rash, fainting, headache, blurred vision, severe swelling, severe dizziness, trouble breathing, irregular heartbeat.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] In healthy individuals, the cortisol level should increase above 18–20 μg/dl within 60 minutes on a 250 mcg cosyntropin stimulation test.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] For standardization across laboratories, the Short Synacthen Test is preferably performed in the morning (between 8:00 AM and 10:00 AM) to account for the diurnal peak of cortisol secretion.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Baseline cortisol is drawn at time 0, with follow‑up samples at 30 minutes (and optionally 60 minutes) after administration of 250 μg synthetic ACTH.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] An adequate response is generally defined as a peak serum cortisol ≥ 500–550 nmol/L (approximately 18–20 μg/dL) or an increment ≥ 200 nmol/L, thresholds that improve diagnostic accuracy for adrenal insufficiency.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] In Addison's disease, both the cortisol and aldosterone levels are low, and the cortisol will not rise during the cosyntropin stimulation test.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Early in the development of secondary adrenal insufficiency, the adrenals may not have atrophied and can still stimulate, resulting in a normal cosyntropin stimulation test.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] If secondary adrenal insufficiency is diagnosed, the insulin tolerance test (ITT) or the CRH (corticotropin-releasing hormone) stimulation test can be used to distinguish between a hypothalamic (tertiary) and pituitary (secondary) cause but is rarely used in clinical practice.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Measuring a morning, fasting ACTH level helps assess for the etiology of adrenal insufficiency.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] ACTH will be high – usually well above upper limits of reference range.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] ACTH will be low – usually below 35, but most people with secondary fall within the range limit.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] This is inappropriately normal for the low cortisol level.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] In some cases, the actual cause of low ACTH is from low CRH in the hypothalamus.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] It is possible to have separate ACTH and CRH impairment such as can happen in a head injury.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] The ACTH stimulation test is occasionally used to test adrenal production of aldosterone at the same time as cortisol to also help in determining if primary (hyperreninemic) or secondary (hyporeninemic) hypoaldosteronism is present.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Human ACTH has a slight stimulatory effect on aldosterone, but the amount of synthetic ACTH given in the stimulation is equivalent to more than a whole days production of natural ACTH, so the aldosterone response can be easily measured in blood serum.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Same as cortisol, aldosterone should double from a respectable base value (around 20 ng/dl, must fast salt 24 hours and sit upright for blood draw) in a healthy individual.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] The aldosterone response in the ACTH stimulation test is blunted or absent in patients with primary adrenal insufficiency including Addison's disease.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] The base value is usually in the mid-teens or less and rise to less than double the base value thus indicating primary hypoaldosteronism (sodium low, potassium and renin enzyme will be high) and is an indicator of primary adrenal insufficiency or Addison's disease.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Aldosterone response of several factors from a low base value.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] This factoring indicates secondary hypoaldosteronism (sodium low, potassium and renin enzyme will be low).
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Usually doubling to quadrupling from a low base aldosterone value is what is seen in secondary adrenal insufficiency.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Decoupling of aldosterone in the ACTH stimulation test is possible (i.e.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] A result of doubling or more of aldosterone may help in tandem with a cortisol stimulation that doubled or more confirm a diagnosis of secondary adrenal insufficiency.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] In rare cases, an aldosterone stimulation which did not double, but with the presence of low potassium, low renin and low ACTH indicates atrophy of aldosterone production from the prolonged lack of renin.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Similar to the cortisol stimulation in ACTH deficiency, the test interpreter may lack knowledge of how to properly interpret for secondary hypoaldosteronism and think a result of aldosterone doubling or more from a low base value is good.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] Recent data showed that Synacthen test results can be used to predict future recovery of HPA axis function in patients with reversible causes of Adrenal Insufficiency.
[src:amylase/acth-stimulation-test] The test is also used to diagnose hypoadrenocorticism in dogs and sometimes cats.
[src:amylase/amy1a] Amylases are secreted proteins that hydrolyze 1,4-alpha-glucoside bonds in oligosaccharides and polysaccharides, and thus catalyze the first step in digestion of dietary starch and glycogen.
[src:amylase/amy1a] The human genome has a cluster of several amylase genes that are expressed at high levels in either salivary gland or pancreas.
[src:amylase/amy1a] This gene encodes an amylase isoenzyme produced by the salivary gland.
[src:amylase/amy1a] Alternative splicing results in multiple transcript variants encoding the same protein.
[src:amylase/amy1c] The human **AMY1C** gene encodes the protein **Amylase, alpha 1C (salivary)**.
[src:amylase/amy1c] The human genome has a cluster of several amylase genes that are expressed at high levels in either the salivary gland or pancreas.
[src:amylase/amy2a] This gene encodes an amylase isoenzyme produced by the pancreas.
[src:amylase/amy2b] Amylases are secreted proteins that hydrolyze 1,4-alpha-glucoside] bonds in oligosaccharides and polysaccharides, and thus catalyze the first step in digestion of dietary starch and glycogen.
[src:amylase/amylase] An **amylase** (/ˈæmɪleɪs/) is an enzyme that catalyses the hydrolysis of starch (Latin *amylum*) into sugars.
[src:amylase/amylase] Amylase is present in the saliva of humans and some other mammals, where it begins the chemical process of digestion.
[src:amylase/amylase] Foods that contain large amounts of starch but little sugar, such as rice and potatoes, may acquire a sweet taste as they are chewed because amylase degrades some of their starch into sugar.
[src:amylase/amylase] The pancreas and salivary glands make amylase (alpha amylase) to hydrolyse dietary starch into disaccharides and trisaccharides, which are converted by other enzymes to glucose to supply the body with energy.
[src:amylase/amylase] Plants and some bacteria also produce amylase.
[src:amylase/amylase] Specific amylase proteins are designated by different Greek letters.
[src:amylase/amylase] All amylases are glycoside hydrolases and act on α-1,4-glycosidic bonds.
[src:amylase/amylase] The α-amylases (EC 3.2.1.1 ) (CAS 9014–71–5) (alternative names: 1,4-α-D-glucan glucanohydrolase; glycogenase) are calcium metalloenzymes.
[src:amylase/amylase] By acting at random locations along the starch chain, α-amylase breaks down long-chain saccharides, ultimately yielding either maltotriose and maltose from amylose; or maltose, glucose, and "limit dextrin" from amylopectin.
[src:amylase/amylase] They belong to glycoside hydrolase family 13 (https://www.cazypedia.org/index.php/Glycoside_Hydrolase_Family_13).
[src:amylase/amylase] Because it can act anywhere on the substrate, α-amylase tends to be faster-acting than β-amylase.
[src:amylase/amylase] In animals, it is a major digestive enzyme, and its optimum pH is 6.7–7.0.
[src:amylase/amylase] In human physiology, both the salivary and pancreatic amylases are α-amylases.
[src:amylase/amylase] The α-amylase form is also found in plants, fungi (ascomycetes and basidiomycetes), and bacteria (*Bacillus*).
[src:amylase/amylase] Another form of amylase, β-amylase (EC 3.2.1.2 ) (alternative names: 1,4-α-D-glucan maltohydrolase; glycogenase; saccharogen amylase) is also synthesized by bacteria, fungi, and plants.
[src:amylase/amylase] Working from the non-reducing end, β-amylase catalyzes the hydrolysis of the second α-1,4 glycosidic bond, cleaving off two glucose units (maltose) at a time.
[src:amylase/amylase] During the ripening of fruit, β-amylase breaks starch into maltose, resulting in the sweet flavor of ripe fruit.
[src:amylase/amylase] They belong to glycoside hydrolase family 14.
[src:amylase/amylase] Both α-amylase and β-amylase are present in seeds: β-amylase is present in an inactive form prior to germination, whereas α-amylase and proteases appear once germination has begun.
[src:amylase/amylase] Many microbes produce amylase to degrade extracellular starches.
[src:amylase/amylase] Animal tissues do not contain β-amylase, although it may be present in microorganisms contained within the digestive tract.
[src:amylase/amylase] The optimum pH for β-amylase is 4.0–5.0.
[src:amylase/amylase] The γ-amylase has the most acidic optimum pH of all amylases, because it is most active around pH 3.
[src:amylase/amylase] They belong to a variety of different glycoside hydrolase families, such as glycoside hydrolase family 15 in fungi, glycoside hydrolase family 31 of human MGAM, and glycoside hydrolase family 97 of bacterial forms.
[src:amylase/amylase] α- and β-amylases are important in brewing beer and liquor made from sugars derived from starch.
[src:amylase/amylase] In fermentation, yeast ingests sugars and excretes ethanol.
[src:amylase/amylase] In beer and some liquors, the sugars present at the beginning of fermentation have been produced by "mashing" grains or other starch sources (such as potatoes).
[src:amylase/amylase] In traditional beer brewing, malted barley is mixed with hot water to create a "mash", which is held at a given temperature to allow the amylases in the malted grain to convert the barley's starch into sugars.
[src:amylase/amylase] Different temperatures optimize the activity of alpha or beta amylase, resulting in different mixtures of fermentable and unfermentable sugars.
[src:amylase/amylase] In selecting mash temperature and grain-to-water ratio, a brewer can change the alcohol content, mouthfeel, aroma, and flavor of the finished beer.
[src:amylase/amylase] In some historic methods of producing alcoholic beverages, the conversion of starch to sugar starts with the brewer chewing grain to mix it with saliva.
[src:amylase/amylase] This practice continues to be practiced in home production of some traditional drinks, such as chhaang in the Himalayas, chicha in the Andes and kasiri in Brazil and Suriname.
[src:amylase/amylase] Amylases are used in breadmaking and to break down complex sugars, such as starch (found in flour), into simple sugars.
[src:amylase/amylase] Yeast then feeds on these simple sugars and converts it into the waste products of ethanol and carbon dioxide.
[src:amylase/amylase] This imparts flavour and causes the bread to rise.
[src:amylase/amylase] While amylases are found naturally in yeast cells, it takes time for the yeast to produce enough of these enzymes to break down significant quantities of starch in the bread.
[src:amylase/amylase] This is the reason for long fermented doughs such as sourdough.
[src:amylase/amylase] Modern breadmaking techniques have included amylases (often in the form of malted barley) into bread improver, thereby making the process faster and more practical for commercial use.
[src:amylase/amylase] α-Amylase is often listed as an ingredient on commercially package-milled flour.
[src:amylase/amylase] Bakers with long exposure to amylase-enriched flour are at risk of developing dermatitis or asthma.
[src:amylase/amylase] In molecular biology, the presence of amylase can serve as an additional method of selecting for successful integration of a reporter construct in addition to antibiotic resistance.
[src:amylase/amylase] As reporter genes are flanked by homologous regions of the structural gene for amylase, successful integration will disrupt the amylase gene and prevent starch degradation, which is easily detectable through iodine staining.
[src:amylase/amylase] Amylase also has medical applications in the use of pancreatic enzyme replacement therapy (PERT).
[src:amylase/amylase] It is one of the components in Sollpura (liprotamase) to help in the breakdown of saccharides into simple sugars.
[src:amylase/amylase] Salivary alpha-amylase serves as a biomarker for physiological stress.
[src:amylase/amylase] Like with other biomarkers for stress, it is known that the salivary alpha-amylase response to stress is reduced in intensity in people with occupational burnout.
[src:amylase/amylase] An inhibitor of alpha-amylase, called phaseolamin, has been tested as a potential diet aid.
[src:amylase/amylase] When used as a food additive, amylase has E number E1100, and may be derived from pig pancreas or mold fungi.
[src:amylase/amylase] Bacilliary amylase is also used in clothing and dishwasher detergents to dissolve starches from fabrics and dishes.
[src:amylase/amylase] Factory workers who work with amylase for any of the above uses are at increased risk of occupational asthma.
[src:amylase/amylase] Five to nine percent of bakers have a positive skin test, and a fourth to a third of bakers with breathing problems are hypersensitive to amylase.
[src:amylase/amylase] Blood serum amylase may be measured for purposes of medical diagnosis.
[src:amylase/amylase] Amylase may be measured in other body fluids, including urine and peritoneal fluid.
[src:amylase/amylase] A January 2007 study from Washington University in St.
[src:amylase/amylase] Louis suggests that saliva tests of the enzyme could be used to indicate sleep deficits, as the enzyme increases its activity in correlation with the length of time a subject has been deprived of sleep.
[src:amylase/amylase] In 1831, Erhard Friedrich Leuchs (1800–1837) described the hydrolysis of starch by saliva, due to the presence of an enzyme in saliva, "ptyalin", an amylase.
[src:amylase/amylase] It was named after the Ancient Greek name for saliva: πτύαλον - *ptyalon*.
[src:amylase/amylase] The modern history of enzymes began in 1833, when French chemists Anselme Payen and Jean-François Persoz isolated an amylase complex from germinating barley and named it "diastase".
[src:amylase/amylase] It is from this term that all subsequent enzyme names tend to end in the suffix -ase.
[src:amylase/amylase] In 1862, Russian biochemist Aleksandr Yakovlevich Danilevsky (1838–1923) separated pancreatic amylase from trypsin.
[src:amylase/amylase] Saccharides are a food source rich in energy.
[src:amylase/amylase] Large polymers such as starch are partially hydrolyzed in the mouth by the enzyme amylase before being cleaved further into sugars.
[src:amylase/amylase] Many mammals have seen great expansions in the copy number of the amylase gene.
[src:amylase/amylase] These duplications allow for the pancreatic amylase *AMY2* to re-target to the salivary glands, allowing animals to detect starch by taste and to digest starch more efficiently and in higher quantities.
[src:amylase/amylase] This has happened independently in mice, rats, dogs, pigs, and most importantly, humans after the agricultural revolution.
[src:amylase/amylase] Following the agricultural revolution 12,000 years ago, human diet began to shift more to plant and animal domestication in place of hunting and gathering.
[src:amylase/amylase] Starch has become a staple of the human diet.
[src:amylase/amylase] Despite the obvious benefits, early humans did not possess salivary amylase, a trend that is also seen in evolutionary relatives of the human, such as chimpanzees and bonobos, who possess either one or no copies of the gene responsible for producing salivary amylase.
[src:amylase/amylase] Like in other mammals, the pancreatic alpha-amylase *AMY2* was duplicated multiple times.
[src:amylase/amylase] One event allowed it to evolve salivary specificity, leading to the production of amylase in the saliva (named in humans as *AMY1*).
[src:amylase/amylase] The 1p21.1 region of human chromosome 1 contains many copies of these genes, variously named *AMY1A*, *AMY1B*, *AMY1C*, *AMY2A*, *AMY2B*, and so on.
[src:amylase/amylase] However, not all humans possess the same number of copies of the *AMY1* gene.
[src:amylase/amylase] Populations known to rely more on saccharides have a higher number of AMY1 copies than human populations that, by comparison, consume little starch.
[src:amylase/amylase] The number of *AMY1* gene copies in humans can range from six copies in agricultural groups such as European-American and Japanese (two high starch populations) to only two to three copies in hunter-gatherer societies such as the Biaka, Datog, and Yakuts.
[src:amylase/amylase] The correlation that exists between starch consumption and number of *AMY1* copies specific to population suggest that more AMY1 copies in high starch populations has been selected for by natural selection and considered the favorable phenotype for those individuals.
[src:amylase/amylase] Therefore, it is most likely that the benefit of an individual possessing more copies of *AMY1* in a high starch population increases fitness and produces healthier, fitter offspring.
[src:amylase/amylase] This fact is especially apparent when comparing geographically close populations with different eating habits that possess a different number of copies of the *AMY1* gene.
[src:amylase/amylase] Such is the case for some Asian populations that have been shown to possess few *AMY1* copies relative to some agricultural populations in Asia.
[src:amylase/amylase] This offers strong evidence that natural selection has acted on this gene as opposed to the possibility that the gene has spread through genetic drift.
[src:amylase/amylase] Variations of amylase copy number in dogs mirrors that of human populations, suggesting they acquired the extra copies as they followed humans around.
[src:amylase/amylase] Unlike humans whose amylase levels depend on starch content in diet, wild animals eating a broad range of foods tend to have more copies of amylase.
[src:amylase/amylase] This may have to do with mainly detection of starch as opposed to digestion.
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] The **AST/ALT ratio** or **De Ritis ratio** is the ratio between the concentrations of two enzymes, aspartate transaminase (AST) and alanine transaminase, a.k.a. alanine aminotransferase (ALT), in the blood of a human or animal.
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] It is used as one of several liver function tests, and measured with a blood test.
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] It is sometimes useful in medical diagnosis for elevated transaminases to differentiate between causes of liver damage, or hepatotoxicity.
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] Most causes of liver cell injury are associated with a greater increase in ALT than AST, but an AST/ALT ratio of 2:1 or greater is suggestive of alcoholic liver disease, particularly in the setting of an elevated gamma-glutamyl transferase.
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] The AST/ALT ratio can also occasionally be elevated in a liver disease pattern in patients with nonalcoholic steatohepatitis, and it is frequently elevated in an alcoholic liver disease pattern in patients with hepatitis C who have developed cirrhosis.
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] In addition, patients with Wilson's disease or cirrhosis due to viral hepatitis may have an AST that is greater than the ALT, though the ratio typically is not greater than two.
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] When the AST is higher than ALT, a muscle source of these enzymes should be considered.
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] For example, muscle inflammation due to dermatomyositis may cause AST > ALT.
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] This is a good reminder that AST and ALT are not good measures of liver function when other sources may influence AST and/or ALT, because they do not reliably reflect the synthesizing ability of the liver, and they may come from tissues other than liver (such as muscle).
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] For example, intense exercise such as weightlifting can increase ALT to 50–200 U/L, and AST to 100–1000 U/L (and raise AST to about four times ALT) for the week following the exercise.
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] The De Ritis ratio is named after Fernando De Ritis, who performed analysis on transaminases in 1957.
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] An AST/ALT ratio >5 necessarily involves extrahepatic tissue, as death of hepatocytes alone would produce an AST/ALT ratio no greater than 2.5.
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] Because the primary cause is extrahepatic, typically an isolated elevated AST is seen, with no change in ALT.
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] Common causes include bone disease, chronic renal failure, lymphoma, and congestive heart failure.
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] In late-stage acute liver damage, the body has had adequate time to clear AST, but not ALT, often resulting in an AST/ALT <1.
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] Since testing typically occurs late in acute viral hepatitis, it is conventionally associated with an AST/ALT ratio <1, though early in the disease, the AST/ALT ratio is often elevated.
[src:amylase/ast-alt-ratio] As the acute liver damage resolves, the body has more time to clear ALT, so in the absence of chronic liver disease, the AST/ALT ratio gradually returns to baseline levels.
